I was curious to see how accurate the displayed ephemeris are (<a href="http://voyager.jpl.nasa.gov/Scripts/distance.js" rel="nofollow">http://voyager.jpl.nasa.gov/Scripts/distance.js</a>) given that they are known very precisely indeed.<p>For instance, ranges to Saturn are known to better than 1km, and Mars to better than 10m (<a href="http://tmo.jpl.nasa.gov/progress_report/42-178/178C.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://tmo.jpl.nasa.gov/progress_report/42-178/178C.pdf</a>, e.g., fig. 1 for Mars), and we don&#x27;t even get to take direct measurements of those bodies as we can for the Voyagers.<p>Alas, the js seems to simply be interpolating between two known values, at a spacing of 1 year (86400s):<p><pre><code>   var epoch_0 = 1373990400;
   var epoch_1 = 1374076800;
    [...]
   var dist_0_v1 = 17396281625.1305;
   var dist_1_v1 = 17395807835.8111;
   current_dist_km_v1 = ( ( ( current_time - epoch_0 ) / ( epoch_1 - epoch_0 ) ) * ( dist_1_v1 - dist_0_v1 ) ) + dist_0_v1;
</code></pre>
I&#x27;m not sure how to square this linear progression over a 1-year span with the comment in the OP that &quot;Because Earth moves around the sun faster than Voyager 1 is traveling from Earth, the distance between Earth and the spacecraft actually decreases at certain times of the year.&quot;
